 Ramakrishnan V.\", TITLE = \"Structure of the 30S ribosomal subunit.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Nature 407:327-339 (2000)\", \"DOI:10.1038/35030006\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:11014183\", AUTHORS = \"Carter AP, Clemons WM, Brodersen DE, Morgan-Warren RJ, Wimberly BT, Ramakrishnan V.\", TITLE = \"Functional insights from the structure of the 30S ribosomal subunit and its interactions with antibiotics.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Nature 407:340-348 (2000)\", \"DOI:10.1038/35030019\"))', 'map03010', 'Ribosome', 'Genetic Information Processing; Translation', 531, 5574, 248, 105, 128, 50, 5275, 299);
INSERT INTO `kegg-pathway-bottleneck`.`pathway_data` (`id`, `code`, `name`, `description`, `class`, `pathway_map`, `module`, `disease`, `dblinks`, `ko_pathway`, `reference`, `eukaryotes_count`, `prokaryotes_count`, `animals_count`, `plants_count`, `fungi_count`, `protists_count`, `bacteria_count`, `archaea_count`) VALUES (204, '03013', 'RNA transport', 'RNA transport from the nucleus to the cytoplasm is fundamental for gene expression. The different RNA species that are produced in the nucleus are exported through the nuclear pore complexes (NPCs) via mobile export receptors. The majority of RNAs, such as tRNAs, rRNAs, and U snRNAs, are transported by specific export receptors, which belong to the karyopherin-beta family proteins. A feature of karyopherins is their regulation by the small GTPase Ran. However, general mRNA export is mechanistically different. Nuclear export of mRNAs is functionally coupled to different steps in gene expression processes, such as transcription, splicing, 3\'-end formation and even translation.', 'Genetic Information Processing; Translation', 'RNA transport', 'Spinal muscular atrophy, Fragile X syndrome, Leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter, Infantile bilateral striatal necrosis, Fragile X tremor/ataxia syndrome, MEHMO syndrome, Beaulieu-Boycott-Innes syndrome', 'GO: 0050658', 'ko03013', 'list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:15519698\", AUTHORS = \"Rodriguez MS, Dargemont C, Stutz F\", TITLE = \"Nuclear export of RNA.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Biol Cell 96:639-55 (2004)\", \"DOI:10.1016/j.biolcel.2004.04.014\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:20733056\", AUTHORS = \"Suzuki T, Izumi H, Ohno M\", TITLE = \"Cajal body surveillance of U snRNA export complex assembly.\", JOURNAL = c(\"J Cell Biol 190:603-12 (2010)\", \"DOI:10.1083/jcb.201004109\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:18313922\", AUTHORS = \"Palancade B, Doye V\", TITLE = \"Sumoylating and desumoylating enzymes at nuclear pores: underpinning their unexpected duties?\", JOURNAL = c(\"Trends Cell Biol 18:174-83 (2008)\", \"DOI:10.1016/j.tcb.2008.02.001\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:17401408\", AUTHORS = \"Pellizzoni L\", TITLE = \"Chaperoning ribonucleoprotein biogenesis in health and disease.\", JOURNAL = c(\"EMBO Rep 8:340-5 (2007)\", \"DOI:10.1038/sj.embor.7400941\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:10872469\", AUTHORS = \"Gingras AC, Raught B, Sonenberg N\", TITLE = \"eIF4 initiation factors: effectors of mRNA recruitment to ribosomes and regulators of translation.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Annu Rev Biochem 68:913-63 (1999)\", \"DOI:10.1146/annurev.biochem.68.1.913\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:11018020\", AUTHORS = \"Asano K, Clayton J, Shalev A, Hinnebusch AG\", TITLE = \"A multifactor complex of eukaryotic initiation factors, eIF1, eIF2, eIF3, eIF5, and initiator tRNA(Met) is an important translation initiation intermediate in vivo.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Genes Dev 14:2534-46 (2000)\", \"DOI:10.1101/gad.831800\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:9548260\", AUTHORS = \"Craig AW, Haghighat A, Yu AT, Sonenberg N\", TITLE = \"Interaction of polyadenylate-binding protein with the eIF4G homologue PAIP enhances translation.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Nature 392:520-3 (1998)\", \"DOI:10.1038/33198\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:15901496\", AUTHORS = \"Reed R, Cheng H\", TITLE = \"TREX, SR proteins and export of mRNA.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Curr Opin Cell Biol 17:269-73 (2005)\", \"DOI:10.1016/j.ceb.2005.04.011\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:16314458\", AUTHORS = \"Tange TO, Shibuya T, Jurica MS, Moore MJ\", TITLE = \"Biochemical analysis of the EJC reveals two new factors and a stable tetrameric protein core.\", JOURNAL = c(\"RNA 11:1869-83 (2005)\", \"DOI:10.1261/rna.2155905\"))', 'map03013', 531, 0, 248, 105, 128, 50, 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `kegg-pathway-bottleneck`.`pathway_data` (`id`, `code`, `name`, `description`, `class`, `pathway_map`, `module`, `disease`, `dblinks`, `ko_pathway`, `reference`, `eukaryotes_count`, `prokaryotes_count`, `animals_count`, `plants_count`, `fungi_count`, `protists_count`, `bacteria_count`, `archaea_count`) VALUES (205, '03015', 'mRNA surveillance pathway', 'The mRNA surveillance pathway is a quality control mechanism that detects and degrades abnormal mRNAs. These pathways include nonsense-mediated mRNA decay (NMD), nonstop mRNA decay (NSD), and no-go decay (NGD). NMD is a mechanism that eliminates mRNAs containing premature translation-termination codons (PTCs). In vertebrates, PTCs trigger efficient NMD when located upstream of an exon junction complex (EJC). Upf3, together with Upf1 and Upf2, may signal the presence of the PTC to the 5\'end of the transcript, resulting in decapping and rapid exonucleolytic digestion of the mRNA. In the NSD pathway, which targets mRNAs lacking termination codons, the ribosome is believed to translate through the 3\' untranslated region and stall at the end of the poly(A) tail. NSD involves an eRF3-like protein, Ski7p, which is hypothesized to bind the empty A site of the ribosome and recruit the exosome to degrade the mRNA from the 3\' end. NGD targets mRNAs with stalls in translation elongation for endonucleolytic cleavage in a process involving the Dom34 and Hbs1 proteins.', 'Genetic Information Processing; Translation', 'mRNA surveillance pathway', 'Oculopharyngeal muscular dystrophy, Pontocerebellar hypoplasia', 'GO: 0071028', 'ko03015', 'list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:15040442\", AUTHORS = \"Maquat LE\", TITLE = \"Nonsense-mediated mRNA decay: splicing, translation and mRNP dynamics.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol 5:89-99 (2004)\", \"DOI:10.1038/nrm1310\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:16723977\", AUTHORS = \"Amrani N, Sachs MS, Jacobson A\", TITLE = \"Early nonsense: mRNA decay solves a translational problem.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol 7:415-25 (2006)\", \"DOI:10.1038/nrm1942\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:17183357\", AUTHORS = \"Eulalio A, Behm-Ansmant I, Izaurralde E\", TITLE = \"P bodies: at the crossroads of post-transcriptional pathways.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol 8:9-22 (2007)\", \"DOI:10.1038/nrm2080\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:18158581\", AUTHORS = \"Mandel CR, Bai Y, Tong L\", TITLE = \"Protein factors in pre-mRNA 3\'-end processing.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Cell Mol Life Sci 65:1099-122 (2008)\", \"DOI:10.1007/s00018-007-7474-3\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:16715045\", AUTHORS = \"Clement SL, Lykke-Andersen J\", TITLE = \"No mercy for messages that mess with the ribosome.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Nat Struct Mol Biol 13:299-301 (2006)\", \"DOI:10.1038/nsmb0406-299\"))', 'map03015', 531, 294, 248, 105, 128, 50, 0, 294);
INSERT INTO `kegg-pathway-bottleneck`.`pathway_data` (`id`, `code`, `name`, `description`, `class`, `pathway_map`, `module`, `disease`, `dblinks`, `ko_pathway`, `reference`, `eukaryotes_count`, `prokaryotes_count`, `animals_count`, `plants_count`, `fungi_count`, `protists_count`, `bacteria_count`, `archaea_count`) VALUES (206, '03018', 'RNA degradation', 'The correct processing, quality control and turnover of cellular RNA molecules are critical to many aspects in the expression of genetic information. In eukaryotes, two major pathways of mRNA decay exist and both pathways are initiated by poly(A) shortening of the mRNA. In the 5\' to 3\' pathway, this is followed by decapping which then permits the 5\' to 3\' exonucleolytic degradation of transcripts. In the 3\' to 5\' pathway, the exosome, a large multisubunit complex, plays a key role. The exosome exists in archaeal cells, too. In bacteria, endoribonuclease E, a key enzyme involved in RNA decay and processing, organizes a protein complex called degradosome. RNase E or R interacts with the phosphate-dependent exoribonuclease polynucleotide phosphorylase, DEAD-box helicases, and additional factors in the RNA-degrading complex.', 'Genetic Information Processing; Folding, sorting and degradation', 'RNA degradation', 'Pontocerebellar hypoplasia, Al-Raqad syndrome', 'GO: 0006401', 'ko03018', 'list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:19239894\", AUTHORS = \"Houseley J, Tollervey D\", TITLE = \"The many pathways of RNA degradation.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Cell 136:763-76 (2009)\", \"DOI:10.1016/j.cell.2009.01.019\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:16968219\", AUTHORS = \"Buttner K, Wenig K, Hopfner KP\", TITLE = \"The exosome: a macromolecular cage for controlled RNA degradation.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Mol Microbiol 61:1372-9 (2006)\", \"DOI:10.1111/j.1365-2958.2006.05331.x\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:16939780\", AUTHORS = \"Schilders G, van Dijk E, Raijmakers R, Pruijn GJ\", TITLE = \"Cell and molecular biology of the exosome: how to make or break an RNA.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Int Rev Cytol 251:159-208 (2006)\", \"DOI:10.1016/S0074-7696(06)51005-8\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:17471261\", AUTHORS = \"Hartung S, Hopfner KP\", TITLE = \"The exosome, plugged.\", JOURNAL = c(\"EMBO Rep 8:456-7 (2007)\", \"DOI:10.1038/sj.embor.7400961\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:17447862\", AUTHORS = \"Carpousis AJ\", TITLE = \"The RNA degradosome of Escherichia coli: an mRNA-degrading machine assembled on RNase E.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Annu Rev Microbiol 61:71-87 (2007)\", \"DOI:10.1146/annurev.micro.61.080706.093440\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:16766188\", AUTHORS = \"Marcaida MJ, DePristo MA, Chandran V, Carpousis AJ, Luisi BF\", TITLE = \"The RNA degradosome: life in the fast lane of adaptive molecular evolution.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Trends Biochem Sci 31:359-65 (2006)\", \"DOI:10.1016/j.tibs.2006.05.005\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:17560162\", AUTHORS = \"Condon C\", TITLE = \"Maturation and degradation of RNA in bacteria.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Curr Opin Microbiol 10:271-8 (2007)\", \"DOI:10.1016/j.mib.2007.05.008\"))', 'map03018', 531, 5573, 248, 105, 128, 50, 5274, 299);
