e lectin-like domains (CTLDs). CLRs function as pattern-recognition receptors (PRRs) for pathogen-derived ligands in dendric cells, macrophages, neutrophils, etc., such as Dectin-1 and Dectin-2 for recognition of fungi-derived B-glucan and high mannose-type carbohydrates. Upon ligand binding, CLRs stimulate intracellular signaling cascades that induce the production of inflammatory cytokines and chemokines, consequently triggering innate and adaptive immunity to pathogens.', 145, 0, 145, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `kegg-pathway-bottleneck`.`pathway_data` (`id`, `code`, `name`, `description`, `class`, `pathway_map`, `module`, `disease`, `dblinks`, `ko_pathway`, `reference`, `eukaryotes_count`, `prokaryotes_count`, `animals_count`, `plants_count`, `fungi_count`, `protists_count`, `bacteria_count`, `archaea_count`) VALUES (307, '04626', 'Plant-pathogen interaction', 'Plants lack animal-like adaptive immunity mechanisms, and therefore have evolved a specific system with multiple layers against invading pathogens. The primary response includes the perception of pathogens by cell-surface pattern-recognition receptors (PRRs) and is referred to as PAMP-triggered immunity (PTI). Activation of FLS2 and EFR triggers MAPK signaling pathway that activates defense genes for antimictobial compounds. The increase in the cytosolic Ca2+ concentration is also a regulator for production of reactive oxygen species and localized programmed cell death/hypersensitive response. The secondary response is called effector-triggered immunity (ETI). Pathogens can acquire the ability to suppress PTI by directly injecting effector proteins into the plant cell through secretion systems. In addition, pathogens can manipulate plant hormone signaling pathways to evade host immune responses using coronatine toxin. Some plants possess specific intracellular surveillance proteins (R proteins) to monitor the presence of pathogen virulence proteins. This ETI occurs with localized programmed cell death to arrest pathogen growth, resulting in cultivar-specific disease resistance.', 'Organismal Systems; Environmental adaptation', 'Plant-pathogen interaction', 'ko04626', 'list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:18206360\", AUTHORS = \"Zipfel C\", TITLE = \"Pattern-recognition receptors in plant innate immunity.\", JOURNAL = c(\"Curr Opin Immunol 20:10-6 (2008)\", \"DOI:10.1016/j.coi.2007.11.003\")), list(REFERENCE = \"PMID:19748302\", AUTHORS = \"Chinchilla D, Shan L, He P, de Vries S, Kemmerling B\", TITLE = \"One for all: